The Presidency issued a statement saying it never received a letter asking for the NPA head to be suspended. JOHANNESBURG Freedom Under Law says it is considering whether to grant the Presidency an extension, on its deadline to suspend National Prosecuting Authority (NPA) head Shaun Abrahams.The Presidency this afternoon issued a statement saying it has checked its records, and it never received a letter asking for Abrahams to be suspended. Just in: The Presidency says it has NOT received a letter from FUL and HSF asking to suspend #ShaunAbrahams and institute an inquiry. pic.twitter.com/qa5YKj4Qq2A week ago, civil society organisations Freedom Under Law and the Helen Suzman Foundation wrote to the president asking that an inquiry be instituted into Abrahams fitness to hold office. They also wanted the two prosecutors responsible for the Pravin Gordhan decision Sibongile Mzinyathi and Torie Pretorius to be suspended.The Presidency says it has no record of receipt of this correspondence and the matter will be attended to once the letter has been delivered. Freedom Under Law s Johan Kreigler says the letter was definitely sent. The fact of the matter is the president has now acknowledged receipt and asked for an extension. We will discuss that with our lawyers. (Edited by Masechaba Sefularo)